####
#### Help about the windows
###############################################################################

@node "ALBWINDOW" "10.1 Album Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.1 Album Window@{ub}

 This is the window that opens first.  The window contains some
 important strings and a "format"-cycle gadget.  It also contains
 several orientation gadgets that you use to move around in your
 register.

 @{fg shine}Artist@{fg text}
    Enter the name af the artist/group here.  When you enter
    something here the titles in the other windows will change
    automatically.  The ask-sign at the end of the string gadget is
    connected to the @{" 'ArtistáWindow '" link "ARTISTWINDOW" 0} window 
    The window opens and show the groupmembers
    if you have entered any together with another album.

 @{fg shine}Title@{fg text}
    Enter the title of the LP/CD/MC etc.  The titles on the other
    windows will change here too.

 @{fg shine}PlayTime@{fg text}
    The total time of the album.

 @{fg shine}Edit/View Comment...@{fg text}
    Brings up a window with more string gadgets.
    See also @{" SongáWindow " link "SONGWINDOW" 0}.

 @{fg shine}Edit/View Songs...@{fg text}
    Brings up a window with info about the tracks on the album.
    See also @{" SongáComments " link "SONGCOMWINDOW" 0}.

 @{fg shine}New@{fg text}
    Makes a new post at the end of the register.

 @{fg shine}Insert@{fg text}
    Inserts a new post in the register.  The post will loose its
    position when you sort the albums.

 @{fg shine}Delete...@{fg text}
    Deletes the selected post from the register.  A requester will
    show up and warn you.  You can't get back what you have
    deleted.

 @{fg shine}Find...@{fg text}
    Pops up the @{" find " link "FINDWINDOW" 0} window.

 @{fg shine}|=====|@{fg text}
    With the slider you can directly select the position in your database
    that you like. You can also use the arrow images on the right side of
    the slider to move one step up/down.

 @{fg shine}|<@{fg text}
    Moves to the first (top) position in the register.

 @{fg shine}<@{fg text}
    Moves one position to the left (higher) in the register.

 @{fg shine}List...@{fg text}
    Opens the @{" Artist-Title-list " link "ATLISTWINDOW" 0} window.

 @{fg shine}>@{fg text}
    Moves one position to the right (lower) in the register.

 @{fg shine}>|@{fg text}
    Moves to the end (bottom) of the register.

 @{fg shine}Format@{fg text}
    This cycle gadget shows the format (media) of your post.
    The following medias are represented:
      CD
      CDS      (CD Single)
      CDM      (CD Maxi)
      MCD      (Mini CD)
      CD+G     (Ordinary CD with some graphics)
      MD    (Mini Disc)
      LD    (Laser Disc)
      LP
      Single
      Maxi
      EP
      MC
      DAT      (Digital Audio Tape)
      DCC      (Digital Comact Cassette)
      Video
      CD-ROM
      Other
      DLP      (D for Double)
      2LP
      3LP
      4LP
      5LP
      DCD      (D for Double)
      2CD
      3CD
      4CD
      5CD

@endnode

@node "SONGWINDOW" "10.2 Song Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.2 Song Window@{ub}

 The Song Window consists of a rather large listview gadget in which
 the different song on the album is shown.  The time of the songs
 are also displayed in the listview gadget.  On the right side of
 the window there are some control gadgets to make the life some
 what simpler.

 @{fg shine}Listview gadget@{fg text}
    This is where you enter the tracks of the album.

 @{fg shine}Add Song@{fg text}
    If you press 'Add Song' a new entry will be made in the
    listview gadget.  Enter the title of the track.  A total of 50
    characters (time included).

 @{fg shine}Add Time@{fg text}
    This button brings up a requester asking for the time of the
    selected track.  Enter the time with your own separators.

 @{fg shine}Delete@{fg text}
    Deletes the selected track from the list.  A requester will
    notify you before you delete a track.

 @{fg shine}Up@{fg text}
    Moves the selected track one position up in the list.

 @{fg shine}Down@{fg text}
    Moves the selected track one position down.

 @{fg shine}Edit/View Comment...@{fg text}
    Opens the @{" 'AlbumáComments'áwindow " link "ALBCOMWINDOW" 0}.

 @{fg shine}GetFile Gadget@{fg text}
    Select the lyrics for the album.  The lyrics should be a normal
    ascii file.  How you wish to type it in, or how other has typed
    it in, is of your own choice.  You select your viewer in the
    prefs window.

 @{fg shine}Edit Lyrics@{fg text}
    Press this button and you will get your own editor (previous
    selected in the tool type).  Enter your lyrics and save the
    file as plain ascii.  Choose the file with the getfile gadget
    and view with the...

 @{fg shine}View Lyrics@{fg text}
    ...button.  Select the viewer in the prefs window and the
    lyrics will appear after pressing this button.

@endnode

@node "ALBCOMWINDOW" "10.3 Album Comments Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.3 Album Comments Window@{ub}

 This window shows the different comments about your album.  You
 enter the information in the string gadgets and press RETURN to
 proceed to the next string gadget. 

 The following information can be stored:

 @{fg shine}View Lyrics@{fg text}

 @{fg shine}Record Company@{fg text}
    Which company who has published the album.

 @{fg shine}Made in@{fg text}
    Which country in which the album has been made in.

 @{fg shine}Cat. Nr.@{fg text}
    Short for 'Catalog Number' -- the number from the record company

 @{fg shine}Cover Design@{fg text} 
    The name(s) of the people(s) responsible for the album cover.

 @{fg shine}Release Date@{fg text}
    When the album was made available for the public.

 @{fg shine}Speed@{fg text}
    Rotation speed of the record (only old vinyls).

 @{fg shine}Recording Technology@{fg text} 
    Applying to digital media such as the CD, the Mini Disc, the DAT and the
    DCC.

 @{fg shine}Video Format@{fg text} 
    Which type of tape the video was recorded on.

 @{fg shine}Rating@{fg text}
    If the record has been reviewed in a magazine you can
    type in the rating here. You can also make your own
    rating scale and type it in here. See @{" Erlandárating " link "ERLAND" 0}
    more information about the 'Erland rating' system.

 @{fg shine}Tape Quality@{fg text} Dolby type and cassette quality for 

 @{fg shine}Cover@{fg text}
    If you have scanned your covers you can choose a path to
    the directory where you keep the pictures and you can use
    your favourite viewer (like Viewtek) to show the pictures.
    You select the viewer in the @{" preferencesáwindow " link "PREFSWINDOW" 0}.

@endnode

@node "SONGCOMWINDOW" "10.4 Song Comments Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.4 Song Comments Window@{ub}

 This is the window were you enter your comments about the lyrics,
 the music and the post production.  There are a lot of string
 gadgets here to, so I write a breif comment about each of them:

 @{fg shine}Music@{fg text}
    The writer of the music.

 @{fg shine}Lyrics@{fg text}
    The writer of the lyrics.

 @{fg shine}Vocals@{fg text}
    Vocalists -- can also be arranger.

 @{fg shine}Mixed by@{fg text}
    The person who mixed the album.

 @{fg shine}Produced by@{fg text}
    The producer of the album.

 @{fg shine}Engineered by@{fg text}
    The recording engineer.

 @{fg shine}Mixed in@{fg text}
    The studio or other facility in which the album were mixed.

 @{fg shine}Recorded in@{fg text}
    The studio where the album were recorded at.

 @{fg shine}Published by@{fg text}
    Publisher of the album -- if other than the record
    company. There could be different publishers in different countries.

 @{fg shine}Other@{fg text}
    Other comments about the album. References to other groups
    or albums etc.

@endnode

@node "ARTISTWINDOW" "10.5 Artist Information Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.5 Artist Information Window@{ub}

 This windows consists mainly of a listview gadget that contains the
 group members.  You enter the name of the new artist in the string
 gadget under the listview gadget.  You can move the artist in the
 list with the arrows on the side.

@endnode

@node "ATLISTWINDOW" "10.6 Artist-Title List Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.6 Artist-Title List Window@{ub}

 All albums are listed here together with thier format.  This list
 reflects the sorting (or lack of such). 

 If you click on an entry it will be made active and displayed

 You may multiselect entries in the list and save then using the
 @{" SaveáSelectedáAs... " link "MENUES" 243} alternative in the Artist-Title List menu.

@endnode

@node "EXPORTWINDOW" "10.7 Export Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.7 Export Window@{ub}

 This is where you export your database in different formats.  You
 can export to three 'destinations'.  They are:

   À Preferences printer
   À ASCII
   À Guide

 If want to use the first option, you have to check your preferences
 settings to ensure that you use the right printer driver.
 AlbIn_MUI will perform a form-feed between every entry in your
 database if have chosen the option to export an entire entry so
 it's easier to seperate the entries.  The 'prefs printer' option is
 the same as the ASCII-export option, except you get your result on
 a paper instead of a file.

 If you export ASCII then you can set the default export directory
 in the @{" preferencesáwindow " link "PREFSWINDOW" 0}.  This also applies to the
 guide-export option.

@endnode

@node "FINDWINDOW" "10.8 Find Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.8 Find Window@{ub}

 I you are lycky you might have so many albums that searching for
 something special might be tiresome if you do it manually.  Well,
 you can always use the find function in AlbIn_MUI to find what you
 search for.  When you open the window, you will see a lot of
 checkmark gadgets.  If you tick them, AlbIn_MUI will search that
 field in every album.  The checkmarks represent every string gadget
 were you can enter text.  There are also a short cut to mark all
 items wich may contain a name of a person or a title of a song or
 an album.  There's also a gadget to clear all checked items when
 you want to make a different search.  You can also ignore the
 casing of the words that you search for which means that if you
 search for 'Energy Rekords', 'energy rekords' as well as 'eNerGY
 rEKorDs' will be found.  If you haven't marked the 'Ignore Case'
 gadget AlbIn_MUI will not find anything.

 You can export the search result as an AlbIn_MUI database.  A file
 requester will pop up so you can enter the name of the new archive.

@endnode

@node "PREFSWINDOW" "10.9 Preferences Window"
@toc "WIN"

@{b}10.9 Preferences Window@{ub}

 This is where you enter the preferences that has to do with
 AlbIn_MUI (the GUI preferences is set by the 'MUI' prefs program).
 The default viewers, editor and paths are set to be most standard
 as possible.  The gadgets at the right are present so you can
 select almost everything with the mouse (you have to enter the
 options by hand).

 @{fg shine}Text viewer@{fg text}
    The command line for your favourite textviewer. The
    default is 'More', hopefully present in the 'C'directory.
    Most text viewers can use the filename as an option
    so it can be read direct (without a file requester).
    The file name should be replaced by '%s' in the
    commandline and AlbIn_MUI will insert the
    name of the file that you have specified. You may
    have to quote the name in case of spaces in the file
    name.

 @{fg shine}Picture viewer@{fg text}
    This is the command line for your picture viewer.
    The same thing applies to the viewer -- '%s' is
    used by AlbIn_MUI to insert the filename.
    Default is 'Display'.

 @{fg shine}Text Editor@{fg text}
    This is the command line for the text editor. If you
    use CygnusEd or GoldEd you might have to use the
    option -sticky. I don't know how Edge or TurboText
    is working so you have to consult your manual to see
    how you send file names as an option to the editor.
    Otherwise the same thing as above still applies to
    this command line. The standard editor is set to Ed
    (it's not the top-of-the-line text editor but it's
    free).

 @{fg shine}Lyric path@{fg text}
    The default path to your lyrics. If you don't select
    a path it will be the current path.

 @{fg shine}Picture Path@{fg text}
    The default path to your cover pictures. Current
    path will be used if you don't select a default
    path.

 @{fg shine}Export Text path@{fg text}
    The text path if you export ascii. The current path
    will be used if you don't specify anything.

 @{fg shine}Export Guide path@{fg text}
    Export path for your giudes. Also set to current path
    if you don't specify.

 @{fg shine}Load Dir@{fg text}
    The directory were you keep the archives to be loaded

 @{fg shine}Save Dir@{fg text}
    The directory were you save your archives (I don't know
    why you would like different paths for saving and loading).

 @{fg shine}Save Options@{fg text}
    Two radio buttons for the save options. If you
    want to be asked to overwrite the old archive everytime
    you select the 'Save' option you should choose the
    latter option, otherwise choose the first option
    and then you won't be bothered by the anoying
    requester.

@endnode

